	    <h1>Our Principles</h1>
	    <p class="lede">The following principles inform our journalistic, design and technology choices.</p>
		
		<ol class="distinct">
			<li><a href="#be-open-and-accountable">Be open and accountable</a></li>
			<li><a href="#publish-for-people-not-to-them">Publish <em>for</em> people, not <em>to</em> them</a></li>
			<li><a href="#were-all-in-this-together">We're all in this together</a></li>
		</ol>
		
		<h2 id="be-open-and-accountable">Be open and accountable</h2>
		
		<p>By making ourselves open and transparent we become more accountable for our actions and are held to a high standard. Our community of users deserve to know who we are and how we work, just as they derserve to know the details of the opperations of Government darpmartments and private companies who represent them.</p>
		
		<p>Australian Government Departments should develop programs to publish data more proactively, to increase accountability of the public service and the public’s engagement with it. <a href="http://agimo.gov.au/files/2013/03/Big-Data-Strategy-Issues-Paper1.pdf">The Department of Finance and Deregulation presented an issues paper on Big Data in March 2013</a>, stating that, ”Big data allows for more focused and evidence-based policy design” and developing proactive data publishing programs may result in “reduction of fraudulent or criminal activity across both government and private sectors”.</p>
		
		<p>We aim to encourage proactive publication of immigration detention data and will actively campaign to facilitate this access.</p>
		
		<p>We aim to set an example with our own publishing standards. Our data and documents should be available for reuse, republishing and remixing. When making publishing decisions, we always start from a default position of openness, using a Creative Commons, Attribution license, and then adding responsible restrictions if necessary (for example, our investigations text will be availble under a Creative Commons Attribution, <em>Non-Commercial</em> Share-Alike license).</p>
		
		<p>Check the bottom of each page for specific copyright licensing information for that content, and always feel free to contact us if you have inquiries about using any of the content published by Detention Logs.</p>
		
		<ul>
		<li>Evidence-based reporting is essential. This involves an assessment of the probative value of facts and the selection, emphasis and use of them based on that assessment.</li>
		</ul>
		
		<h2 id="publish-for-people-not-to-them">Publish <em>for</em> people, not <em>to</em> them</h2>
		
		<p>The primary goal of Detention Logs is to provide the public with the facts they need to better understand the reality of Australia’s immigration detention network. Across our editorial, design and publishing practices, we judge the success of our choices against how our work is used to support more informed policy discussion and challenge inhumane policy based on spin. We provide information to be engaged with and pulled apart by our audience, rather than just accepted passively.</p>
